Fossils from an extinct pygmy sperm whale that died seven million years ago shed new light on the evolution of modern day whales . 
  The remains were discovered in Panama and indicate the organ involved in sound generation and echolocation got smaller throughout the whale’s evolution . 
  Nanokogia isthmia is known from the well-preserved skulls of two individuals unearthed at a sea cliff along the Caribbean coast of Panama . 
  At one time small sperm whales had a much larger spermaceti organ relative to their size . 
  In contrast modern sperm whales are much larger than their extinct relatives . 
  Find will help experts fill in gaps in the evolution of cetaceans . 
 